[{"type": "markdown", "source": "# Understanding List Comprehensions in Python\nThis lesson will guide you through the concept of list comprehensions, showing how they can simplify your code when creating lists."}, {"type": "code", "source": "# Setup check \u2014 run me first\nimport importlib, sys\nREQUIRED = {}  # No additional packages required\nmissing = [f\"{m} ({hint})\" for m, hint in REQUIRED.items()\n           if importlib.util.find_spec(m) is None]\nif missing:\n    raise SystemExit(\"Missing prerequisites:\\n  - \" + \"\\n  - \".join(missing))\nprint(\"Setup OK \u2014 Python\", sys.version.split()[0])"}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "## Basic Syntax of List Comprehensions\nList comprehensions allow you to create lists in a more concise way than using loops. Here's the basic syntax:"}, {"type": "code", "source": "# Example of basic list comprehension\nsquares = [x**2 for x in range(10)]\nprint(squares)"}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "The output should show a list containing the squares of numbers from 0 to 9."}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "## Transforming For-Loops into List Comprehensions\nYou can replace a standard for-loop that appends to a list with a single line of code using a list comprehension."}, {"type": "code", "source": "# Transforming a for-loop into a list comprehension\nsquares_loop = []\nfor x in range(10):\n    squares_loop.append(x**2)\nprint(squares_loop)"}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "The output should match the previous example, demonstrating the equivalence of the two approaches."}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "## Adding Conditional Logic\nList comprehensions can include conditions to filter items. Here's how you can do that."}, {"type": "code", "source": "# List comprehension with a condition\neven_squares = [x**2 for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]\nprint(even_squares)"}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "The output should show the squares of even numbers from 0 to 9."}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "## Nested List Comprehensions\nYou can also create lists of lists with nested comprehensions. Here's an example."}, {"type": "code", "source": "# Nested list comprehension\nmatrix = [[j for j in range(3)] for i in range(3)]\nprint(matrix)"}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "The output should show a 3x3 matrix, demonstrating the use of nested list comprehensions."}, {"type": "markdown", "source": "## Takeaway\nList comprehensions are a powerful feature in Python that can make your code more readable and concise. They can be used for simple transformations, filtering, and even nested structures."}]